Student reaction mixed

to U.S. attack on Iraq

By Renee Crespy

and Margaret Swisher
Slaﬂ’ Writers

Ten minutes after the United
States declared war on Baghdad,
students sat in the William Pitt
Union's Assembly Room with
their eyes ﬁxed on Cable News
Network’s report on the war.

Student reactions were mixed,
yet the majority of the students
felt the U.S. action was “scary, yet
necessary."

.“I feel it’s the United States’
responsibility as one of the
superpowers of the world  to
do this to keep it under check,"
said Pitt stu_,dent Raymond
Spelling. “I have friends there,
and I hadn’t thought about their
safety until I walked out of class
and heard. Then realization set in
that I might never see [them]
again.”

Becky Tedesco, whose brother
is in the Army reserves and could
get called for active duty, is scared

but supportive.

“I think it’s necessary, but like
everyone else, I’m scared. I
support my brother 100 percent,
but I don’t think Saddam [Hussein]
could be negotiated with. He’s
crazy," Tedesco said.

“I’m not scared,” said Bob
Tedesco, her brother. “It’s what
you do when you sign the papers
to be in the Army.”

Aida and Raida Khalil, two
sisters from Syria, are worried
about their families, who they
have not been able to contact.

“I’m stunned," said a teary-eyed
Raida. “I have aunts and uncles
over there that I haven't been
able to get in touch with. I’m
afraid that this might escalate into
World War III.”

“I think of the draft and all the
people that would go,” said Aida.
“I know it sounds strange, but
they just should have left things
alone.”

