Pz'tt- experts comment
on situation in Gulf

By Mark Staf
Stajf Writer

Pitt Professor Theodore Windt, a noted political commentator,
described his reaction to the U.S.—led attack on Iraq with “great
sadness.”

Windt, who teaches in the communications and rhetoric
department, said comparisons to Vietnam do not apply to the
situation in the Persian Gulf. He said, “The interesting thing I’ve
found was this talk about ‘This is not going to be another
Vietnam.’ That’s very important in the sense of the basic
argument—standing up to aggression and stopping aggression.
But because of Vietnam and the inglorious end to that war,
those who oppose the war have been using the Vietnam
analogy that this is another Vietnam.

“I don’t think it’s similar in that Vietnam was a guerilla war
in which you were fighting small groups of guerillas, and you
didn’t know where they would attack. There was no air war in
Vietnam. We controllledl the air in that North Vietnam had no
air force; it [also] had no navy. There was never a major
confrontation of a large massing of troops on one side and a
large massing on the other, as we have right now on the border
of Kuwait,” he said.

Windt also said that he was not surprised about the moves
Saddam Hussein has made since his invasion of Kuwait.
However, Windt feels that war still could have been avoided.

