The calm after the Desert Storm

At precisely 7 p.m. Eastern Standard Time
(3 a.m. Iraqi time) onjan. 16, 1991, the first
bombs were dropped as the war against
Iraq officially began.

In an address to the nation, President
Bush stated that ‘the United States had now
“joined the war.” In what could possibly be
the most devastating war of the century,
Bush ironically quoted Master Sgt. J.P.

A EDITORIAL

Kendall of the 82nd Airborne as saying,
“We’re here for more than just the price of
a gallon of gas. What we’re doing is going
to chart the future of the world for the next
100 years.”

The Reagan and Bush administrations
have been hugely successful in military
actions taken against Grenada, Libya and
Panama. However, the war with Iraq has
vastly different connotations, with a much
greater risk to our nation and to the world.
We face a possible chemical war and the
loss of billions of gallons of oil from the
world market. There is also tremendous
fear of an increase in worldwide terrorism.
The fact that the United States plays such a
leading role in this situation increases this
potential danger.

Many people supporting Bush are citing
the Munich Conference of 1936. At this
time, the Allies allowed Hitler to keep
conquered territories in order to maintain
peace. Hitler used the Allies’ diplomacy as
a means to strengthen his forces and start
World War II.

While this is a strong argument, it must be
understood that the United States should
not presume the roleof world police. The
fact that the United States sent a force before
the United Nations passed a resolution to
use force in the Persian Gulf undermined
the authority of the United Nations.

Now it seems that Bush has given us only
two possible futures. If Operation Desert
Storm succeeds in driving Saddam Hussein
and Iraqi forces out of Kuwait, it will set a
precedent for the United States to use

military force in diplomatic situations. In
spite of a faltering economy, Bush will be
re-elected in 1992 by riding on the coattails
of this massive military victory.

If Operation Desert Storm fails, it will be
at the expense of many lives and a probable
devastation of the area, and it will pave the
way for enormous structural changes in the
Middle Eastern political arena. v_ Bush’s

chances of a second term in office would be
destroyed. The next president of the United
States will be elected on the promise that
our country will stay out of foreign diplomatic
and political disputes and will not deploy
U.S. troops to foreign soil.

In either scenario, the effects will be long
term, especially in foreign policy. In the
19305 U.S. foreign policy was so isolationist
that it prevented us from entering World
War II. After our successful role in this war,
our policy became so interventionist that in
the 19505 and ’60s we were involved in the
civil wars of Korea and Vietnam. In the
1980s, Panama and Grenada erased the
doubts the American public had about U.S.
foreign policy.

The situation in the gulf has the world
anxiously watching. The next move from
either side could have profound implications
that go far beyond the political realm. The
whole world is watching for news on their
sons and daughters, for burning oil fields
having potentially disastrous effects on the
environment and for the possible crash of
fragile economic situations worldwide.

We at the University of Pittsburgh have
seen have great division over the war here
on campus. Like the rest of the country, we
should be supportive of our troops, as they
are not the policy-makers. Rather, we hope
that they will return home soon.

We hope that Operation Desert Storm is
successful. Not because we approve the use
of military force in this situation, but because
the scenario if Desert Storm fails would be
horrific. We must maintain a state of level-
headedness. Even if Operation Desert Storm
is swift and the damage minimal, we will be
reminded of its debris for a long time to
come.

