the team is working on more
difficult routines now, which
aren’t polished at this point.

Pitt beat William and Mary
at the Metro Invitational by
just 2.1 points, hardly a wide
enough margin to give the
Panthers much breathing room
in Saturday's meet.

D’Amico said the meet may
be decided after the floor
exercise, the first event. Floor
is William and Mary’s best
event and one in which Pitt is
struggling now because of
injuries.

Jorge Gonzalez (Achilles’
tendon), Genaro Severino
(knee) and Brock Freehling
(ankle), three of Pitt’s top

competitors on floor, are all
suffering from injuries which
prevent them from performing
their most difficult routines.

“Conceivably, we can be
down by two points after the
first event,” D’Amico said. If
that’s the case, Pitt will be
playing catch-up for the
remainder of the meet and
will need to hit every routine
in more difficult events like
pommel horse.

D’Amico added, however,
“If we’re winning after floor, I
think we’ll pull away from
them.”

“Because ﬂoor is [William
and Mary’s] best event, I’m
expecting a close meet,”
D’Amico said. “I would like to
know that we can go in there
and win by 10 points, but I
can’t say that. Their team is
very good this year. It’s not
like they’re going to give
anything away. If it isn’t a
close meet, I’ll be surprised.”

Last year, Pitt finished at 10-
7, and made dramatic
improvements from the

beginning of the season to the
end. D’Amico even remarked
it was the best team he’d ever
had. His outlook this year is
even more positive.

“We’re three times better
than we were last year," he
said.

