UNIVERSITY OF PITTSBURGH

By Manny Theiner
For the Pitt News

Does Pittsburgh really have a music
scene? The city’s got plenty of dime—a—
dozen Top 40, thrash—metal, rhythm and
blues, “progressive” (i.e. New Wave circa
1983), re ggae and hi ppie/ folk poontangers.
But if you’re talking about the late—’80s
post-punk underground independent rock
scene, you can almost forget it. Two bands
have attracted a lot of attention outside of
Pittsburgh in places where people know
what's up — Sludgehammer and the
Northern Bushmen.

These groups are caught in limbo
between two long-established camps at
the Oakland club. They are ignored by the
jangly, alternative poser crowd, yet they
aren’t accepted by the hardcore scene
either. “We have ‘moshable’ parts in our
songs,” says Sludgehammer bassist Brian
Welcker. “They just start and stop too
much for the punks to figure out.”

That remark may at first seem strange,
considering that their first show was in
drummer Ian Williams’ living room, back
when he lived with members of the
hardcore band Necracedia. From then on,
Sludgehammer developed a self-described
“college— geek” sound, drawing on various
indie—rock inﬂuences that easily suggested
their suitability in supporting acts like H.P.
Zinker and Bitch Magnet at The Upstage.

The Northern Bushmen had a different
genesis, since they were all high—school
students (three are still 16 years old) when
the band was formed last year. “Pat [Morris]
used to jam with me in my basement,”
recalls drummer Noah Leger, “and I met
Chris [Kleinerl while going to school at
CAPA. I don’t know where we got Mike
lRhoadsl."

They derived inspiration from hanging

