“Life in the movie business is
like the  beginning of a new
love affair: it’s full of surprises,
and you’re constantly getting
fucked.”

Welcome to David Mamet’s
Hollywood.

Mamet’s Speed-the-Plow,
currently being staged at the
Pittsburgh Public Theater under
the direction of Mel Shapiro,
attacks the evils of Hollywood,
particularly the film industry, in a
way similar to Nathaniel West’s
Day of the Locust.

Speed—tbe-Plow focuses on
Bobby Gould (David Butler), who
has just been promoted to head
of productions at a big-name
studio. Charlie Fox Games
Anthony Shanta), a struggling

THE P1'I'I' NEWS, Thursday, January 17, 1990

producer who’s been loyal to
Gould for 11 years, finds a script
with get— rich potential and even
secures a “star” for the major role.

Everything appears to be going
smoothly until Karen (Ming-Na
Wen), a temporary secretary,
shows up. Fox bets Gould 5500
that he will never get Karen in
bed.

Gould gets Karen and the
money, under the stipulation that
he makes a meaningful film out
of an Eastern philosophy book
about the end of the world.

Although the characters seem
unethical, each of them possesses
some strange virtue that appears
odd in this “sinkhole of slime and
depravity.” Fox’s loyalty to Gould
seems out of place, and Karen’s
conviction to make the
philosophy movie is undying.

